\begin_body

\begin_layout Title
\SpecialChar LaTeX
 for Intermediates
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subtitle
Glossaries and Index
\end_layout

\begin_layout Author
Elisabeth Maria Magin
\end_layout

\begin_layout Date
09.12.2025
\end_layout

\begin_layout Abstract
This document is an active demonstration and learning document showing how to create a combined index and glossary using \SpecialChar LaTeX
 and the \SpecialChar LyX
 user interface.
 The package used for this purpose is the 
\begin_inset CommandInset href
LatexCommand href
name "glossaries package"
target "https://ctan.org/pkg/glossaries"
literal "false"

\end_inset

,
 which requires the use of code in the \SpecialChar LyX
 document.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Loading additional \SpecialChar LaTeX
 packages via the preamble
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Unlike the nomenclature package,
 which also provides glossary features,
 the glossaries package has not been integrated into \SpecialChar LyX
 yet.
 This means that the package cannot be chosen and loaded by choosing a module,
 but needs to be added to the preamble via 
\emph on
Document > Settings > LaTeX Preamble.

\emph default
 Adding 
\begin_inset Quotes xld
\end_inset


\backslash
usepackage{glossaries}
\begin_inset Quotes xrd
\end_inset

 activates the package.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Setting options for the glossaries package
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
glossaries is an extensive,
 very versatile package with features that vastly exceed what the nomenclature package can offer.
 With it not being part of \SpecialChar LyX
 yet,
 several options for it need to be set manually.
 In the preamble,
 add [automake,
 acronym,
 shortcuts,
 toc] to the 
\backslash
usepackage command:
 
\backslash
usepackage[automake,
 acronym,
 shortcuts,
 toc]{glossaries}.
 The first is required to automatically run background processes that create your glossary,
 while 
\begin_inset Quotes xld
\end_inset

acronym
\begin_inset Quotes xrd
\end_inset

 allows you to create extensible acronyms in addition to glossary entries,
 
\begin_inset Quotes xld
\end_inset

shortcuts
\begin_inset Quotes xrd
\end_inset

 permits the use of shorter commands in the text and 
\begin_inset Quotes xld
\end_inset

toc
\begin_inset Quotes xrd
\end_inset

 automatically adds a table of contents-entry for your glossary.
 You can remove the latter three if you don't need them,
 
\begin_inset Quotes xld
\end_inset

automake
\begin_inset Quotes xrd
\end_inset

 is required at least in \SpecialChar LyX
 for glossaries to work properly.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Secondly,
 you need to instruct the computer to create a glossary by adding 
\begin_inset Quotes xld
\end_inset


\backslash
makeglossaries
\begin_inset Quotes xrd
\end_inset

 in the preamble below the 
\backslash
usepackage{glossaries} command.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
You further need to move to the 
\emph on
Indexes
\emph default
 tab in your document settings and choose 
\begin_inset Quotes xld
\end_inset

makeindex
\begin_inset Quotes xrd
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Quotes xld
\end_inset

xindy
\begin_inset Quotes xrd
\end_inset

 as 
\emph on
Index Generation.

\emph default
 Both are compatible with the glossaries package.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Creating and adding your glossary file
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Because this isn't a package build into \SpecialChar LyX
 yet,
 you need to create your glossary file as a .tex-file and load it via the preamble.
 The command is 
\begin_inset Quotes xld
\end_inset


\backslash
loadglsentries{path/to/your/file}
\begin_inset Quotes xrd
\end_inset

.
 Add it below 
\backslash
makeglossaries in the 
\emph on
LaTeX Preamble
\emph default
 tab.
 If you keep your glossary file in the same directory as your \SpecialChar LyX
 document,
 you don't need to add a path,
 you simply add the file name 
\series bold
without
\series default
 the file extension.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To create your glossary file,
 open a text editor (Notepad++,
 VS Code,
 KATE) and save the document in the same folder as your \SpecialChar LyX
 document,
 with a name like 
\begin_inset Quotes xld
\end_inset

glossaryfile
\begin_inset Quotes xrd
\end_inset

 and the extension 
\begin_inset Quotes xld
\end_inset

tex
\begin_inset Quotes xrd
\end_inset

:
 glossaryfile.tex.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Creating a glossary entry
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now you can move on to creating a new glossary entry.
 The minimum information the system needs is a keyword that calls the entry,
 the name and a description,
 for example 
\begin_inset Quotes xld
\end_inset


\backslash
newglossaryentry{glossary}{name={glossary},
 description={A list and explanation of relevant terms,
 usually used in scientific publications,
 where not everyone may be equally familiar with the terms}}
\begin_inset Quotes xrd
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The command syntax itself is 
\begin_inset Quotes xld
\end_inset


\backslash
newglossaryentry{}{}.
 The first pair of curly brackets contains the 
\series bold
label
\series default
 by which you refer to the glossary term – in the above example,
 that term is 
\begin_inset Quotes xld
\end_inset

glossary
\begin_inset Quotes xrd
\end_inset

.
 The second pair of curly brackets wraps around the basic required information:
 the 
\series bold
name
\series default
 that appears when you call the glossary item in your text,
 and the 
\series bold
description
\series default
 that will appear in your glossary at the end of the file.
 These are,
 respectively,
 entered with 
\begin_inset Quotes xld
\end_inset

name = {}
\begin_inset Quotes xrd
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Quotes xld
\end_inset

description = {}
\begin_inset Quotes xrd
\end_inset

,
 separated by a comma.
 Note that the 
\series bold
second
\series default
 closing curly bracket 
\series bold
always
\series default
 comes 
\series bold
after
\series default
 the closing curly bracket that wraps the description:
 
\backslash
newglossaryentry{}{name={},
 description={}}
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The glossaries package can automatically create a plural of your term by adding -s to the end of the 
\series bold
name
\series default
.
 If your term's plural is 
\series bold
not
\series default
 created by adding -s,
 you need to specify the plural form,
 as is the case for 
\begin_inset Quotes xld
\end_inset

glossary
\begin_inset Quotes xrd
\end_inset

,
 where the plural is 
\begin_inset Quotes xld
\end_inset

glossaries
\begin_inset Quotes xrd
\end_inset

.
 You do this by adding 
\begin_inset Quotes xld
\end_inset

plural = {glossaries}
\begin_inset Quotes xrd
\end_inset

 in the second pair of curly brackets,
 between 
\series bold
name
\series default
 and 
\series bold
description:

\series default
 
\backslash
newglossaryentry{glossary}{name={glossary},
 
\series bold
plural={glossaries},

\series default
 description={A list and explanation of relevant terms,
 usually used in scientific publications,
 where not everyone may be equally familiar with the terms}}
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Creating an acronym entry
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
With glossaries,
 you can also use acronyms which can automatically be shortened and extended as you wish.
 The syntax to create a new acronym entry is 
\begin_inset Quotes xld
\end_inset


\backslash
newacronym{}{}{}
\begin_inset Quotes xrd
\end_inset

.
 The first curly bracket again contains the 
\series bold
label
\series default
 – in this case,
 we'll be using 
\begin_inset Quotes xld
\end_inset

MP
\begin_inset Quotes xrd
\end_inset

.
 The second curly bracket contains the 
\series bold
acronym,

\series default
 which in this case will also be 
\begin_inset Quotes xld
\end_inset

MP
\begin_inset Quotes xrd
\end_inset

.
 The third curly bracket contains the 
\series bold
term
\series default
 that is abbreviated by the acronym,
 
\begin_inset Quotes xld
\end_inset

Member of Parliament
\begin_inset Quotes xrd
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Again,
 the glossaries package automatically extends acronyms into plural forms by attaching an -s.
 In this case,
 this is only correct for the short form – the plural of 
\begin_inset Quotes xld
\end_inset

MP
\begin_inset Quotes xrd
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Quotes xld
\end_inset

MPs
\begin_inset Quotes xrd
\end_inset

.
 It is not correct for the term:
 
\begin_inset Quotes xld
\end_inset

Member of Parliaments
\begin_inset Quotes xrd
\end_inset

 is not the correct plural for 
\begin_inset Quotes xld
\end_inset

Member of Parliament
\begin_inset Quotes xrd
\end_inset

.
 Therefore the correct plural again needs to be defined by adding 
\series bold
optional
\series default
 information in [] between 
\backslash
newacronym and the three curly braces:
 [longplural = {Members of Parliament}].
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This will give us the complete entry as 
\backslash
newglossaryentry[longplural = {Members of Parliament}]{mp}{MP}{Member of Parliament}
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Analogue to this,
 if the acronym's plural is different,
 this can be set by adding 
\begin_inset Quotes xld
\end_inset

shortplural = {correct plural of the acronym}
\begin_inset Quotes xrd
\end_inset

 inside the [].
 If both the short and the long plural need to be defined,
 remember to separate the two definitions by a 
\series bold
comma
\series default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Adding terms into your text
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To use the glossary entries in your LyX document,
 you need to use Evil Red Boxes,
 a.k.a.
 actual \SpecialChar LaTeX
 code.
 Acronyms are always automatically extended on first appearance in the text,
 with the acronym added in brackets after the full term.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
a linked glossary term in the text:
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
gls{latex}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
a linked glossary term in the plural in the text:
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
glspl{glossary}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
a linked acronym on the first occurrence:
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
ac{mp}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
a linked acronym on the second occurrence:
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
ac{mp}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
a linked acronym plural:
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
acp{mp}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
a linked acronym spelled out:
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
acl{mp}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
a linked acronym plural spelled out:
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
aclp{mp}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Terms are capitalised by capitalising the first letter of the command:
 
\backslash
Gls,
 
\backslash
Glspl,
 
\backslash
Ac,
 
\backslash
Acp,
 
\backslash
Acl,
 
\backslash
Aclp.
 They can also be capitalised entirely by using 
\backslash
GLS,
 
\backslash
AC etc.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If you added the 
\begin_inset Quotes xld
\end_inset

shortcuts
\begin_inset Quotes xrd
\end_inset

 option when you called the glossaries package,
 you can use 
\backslash
ac instead of 
\backslash
gls,
 
\backslash
acp instead of 
\backslash
glspl,
 etc.,
 which makes typing a little less cumbersome.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If you need to 
\series bold
change
\series default
 your term,
 you 
\series bold
always
\series default
 change the glossary entry in glossaryfile.tex,
 
\series bold
never
\series default
 the label.
 For example,
 if you need to change 
\begin_inset Quotes xld
\end_inset

Member of Parliament
\begin_inset Quotes xrd
\end_inset

 into 
\begin_inset Quotes xld
\end_inset

Member of Stortinget
\begin_inset Quotes xrd
\end_inset

,
 you only change the 
\series bold
relevant parts
\series default
 in the glossary entry:
 
\backslash
newacronym[longplural={Members of 
\series bold
Stortinget
\series default
}]{mp}{M
\series bold
S
\series default
}{Member of 
\series bold
Stortinget
\series default
}
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
On recompilation,
 your entries in the text and the glossary will be automatically updated.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Printing your glossary
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Finally,
 you need to print your glossary.
 Again this needs to be done with a Evil Red Text.
 Add 
\begin_inset Quotes xld
\end_inset


\backslash
printglossary
\begin_inset Quotes xrd
\end_inset

 in your text where you want your glossary to be printed.
 You can also optionally change the title:
 
\begin_inset Quotes xld
\end_inset


\backslash
printglossary[title = {New title}
\begin_inset Quotes xrd
\end_inset

 will use the text in the curly brackets as the heading for the glossary.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
printglossary[type = main,title = {Glossar}]
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To print your acronyms,
 add 
\begin_inset Quotes xld
\end_inset


\backslash
printglossary[type = acronym]
\begin_inset Quotes xrd
\end_inset

 to your document where you want the list to be printed.
 Again,
 you can change the title if you prefer:
 
\begin_inset Quotes xld
\end_inset


\backslash
printglossary[type = acronym,
 title = {My list of acronyms}
\begin_inset Quotes xrd
\end_inset

 will change it.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
printglossary[type = acronym]
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_body
\end_document
